WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.074
Watch Online Movies and Series for FREE
www.osdb.link/lm

2
00:00:12.345 --> 00:00:14.514
When I was a kid
growing up in New York.

3
00:00:14.597 --> 00:00:18.601
my job after school
was folding mountains of pizza boxes.

4
00:00:22.147 --> 00:00:24.858
They said. "You've tried the rest.
now try the best."

5
00:00:24.941 --> 00:00:27.110
which everyone's boxes said.

6
00:00:28.695 --> 00:00:31.990
Looking at that box. I just thought.
"This might not be true."

7
00:00:32.532 --> 00:00:34.743
"This might be somewhat biased."

8
00:00:36.161 --> 00:00:38.705
Oh really? You use that same
bromated. bleached flour?

9
00:00:38.788 --> 00:00:40.457
That same block of cheese?

10
00:00:41.207 --> 00:00:45.170
What magic could these hands do
to these same ingredients?

11
00:00:48.131 --> 00:00:50.341
I would hear people say. "It's the water."

12
00:00:52.635 --> 00:00:53.928
I love wood ovens.

13
00:00:55.388 --> 00:00:56.556
Is that the secret?

14
00:00:57.390 --> 00:00:58.390
It's not.

15
00:00:58.892 --> 00:01:00.018
Here's the secret.

16
00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:02.562
Shit in. shit out. You know?

17
00:01:03.980 --> 00:01:06.691
You put crap in there. crap's comin' out.

18
00:01:08.485 --> 00:01:10.153
Put good things in an oven.

19
00:01:11.071 --> 00:01:13.615
then we have an opportunity
to make something good happen.

20
00:02:34.112 --> 00:02:37.240
I did this book
where I went around the country.

21
00:02:37.866 --> 00:02:38.866
and went to Italy.

22
00:02:40.368 --> 00:02:43.079
I ate a thousand slices of pizza
in one year.

23
00:02:44.664 --> 00:02:46.082
And I said in my book.

24
00:02:46.749 --> 00:02:48.334
"The best pizza in the world

25
00:02:48.877 --> 00:02:50.920
is made in Phoenix. Arizona."

26
00:02:53.089 --> 00:02:56.551
People thought it was the most
blasphemous thing you could say.

27
00:02:56.634 --> 00:02:59.512
"Oh. it's not made in New York?"
Or. "It's not made in Italy?"

28
00:03:00.555 --> 00:03:03.933
The food critic at Vogue said.
"You know. you're insane."

29
00:03:04.851 --> 00:03:09.439
I was like.
"Okay. go to Phoenix. eat the pizza."

30
00:03:09.522 --> 00:03:10.523
"Talk to me."

31
00:03:12.233 --> 00:03:15.737
He calls me from the airport.

32
00:03:16.362 --> 00:03:18.156
He says. "You were right."

33
00:03:21.534 --> 00:03:24.537
When I went to meet
Chris Bianco for the first time.

34
00:03:24.621 --> 00:03:27.165
he was this sort of Yoda
of the pizza oven.

35
00:03:27.874 --> 00:03:33.713
He was talking about pizza.
the desert. and how he fit in it all.

36
00:03:34.422 --> 00:03:36.257
The last one to go outside. Here.

37
00:03:36.341 --> 00:03:37.634
It was dizzying.

38
00:03:38.259 --> 00:03:41.471
but you're gonna look at pizza differently
after hanging out with Chris Bianco.

39
00:03:43.473 --> 00:03:44.891
Drop it. baby. drop the ball.

40
00:03:48.353 --> 00:03:51.564
Chris has this really abrasive exterior.

41
00:03:51.648 --> 00:03:53.775
and he says "fuck" a lot
and all of those things.

42
00:03:53.858 --> 00:03:55.777
but he's so. so sweet.

43
00:03:57.737 --> 00:04:01.074
He wants to make people feel good.
and that'll keep him up at night.

44
00:04:03.076 --> 00:04:07.163
There's something of an old-school
New York cab driver about him.

45
00:04:08.373 --> 00:04:10.750
But Chris
is the Coltrane of pizza.

46
00:04:10.833 --> 00:04:12.460
This guy remade the game.

47
00:04:16.422 --> 00:04:20.385
Before Chris. people were using
canned pizza sauce.

48
00:04:21.469 --> 00:04:22.971
generic flour.

49
00:04:24.555 --> 00:04:27.642
Chris elevated every ingredient.

50
00:04:28.268 --> 00:04:31.771
He said. "It's worth doing right."

51
00:04:32.689 --> 00:04:37.110
And now. if you look across the country.
in all 50 states.

52
00:04:37.193 --> 00:04:39.279
you can find pizza

53
00:04:39.362 --> 00:04:42.490
that has been inspired
by something that Chris did.

54
00:04:43.616 --> 00:04:47.578
He basically started
the pizza revolution in this country.

55
00:05:00.133 --> 00:05:03.011
Marg. Wiseguy.

56
00:05:03.886 --> 00:05:06.973
There's something else for 'em.
Wanna take that to the table outside?

57
00:05:07.056 --> 00:05:09.434
Now. we've got a Wiseguy coming...

58
00:05:14.397 --> 00:05:17.066
All right. friends.
we got pizza rolling up.

59
00:05:17.150 --> 00:05:20.903
Wiseguy. smoked mozzarella.
fennel sausage. roasted onion.

60
00:05:24.115 --> 00:05:26.701
Being a kid from New York.
we think we know everything.

61
00:05:27.660 --> 00:05:31.831
The Yankees are the best.
Your mom's meatballs are the best.

62
00:05:32.665 --> 00:05:34.459
But what makes it the best anyway?

63
00:05:36.669 --> 00:05:39.297
I'll never forget
my first trip to Italy.

64
00:05:40.923 --> 00:05:44.594
We went to a little trattoria.
A really simple meal.

65
00:05:46.387 --> 00:05:49.807
I remember thinking about
what dessert was gonna be.

66
00:05:51.184 --> 00:05:52.810
It'd be a big rum cake?

67
00:05:53.811 --> 00:05:54.896
Cannoli?

68
00:05:55.980 --> 00:05:57.607
And then dessert came.

69
00:05:57.690 --> 00:05:59.484
There was a guy pushin' on

70
00:05:59.567 --> 00:06:02.362
a shaky little cart with this pewter bowl.

71
00:06:02.445 --> 00:06:05.406
beaded with sweat from the ice in it.

72
00:06:06.991 --> 00:06:12.705
And in that bowl was just peaches.
bobbing like apples in this ice bath.

73
00:06:13.831 --> 00:06:16.542
And I thought. "What am I gonna do
with this peach?"

74
00:06:19.128 --> 00:06:20.963
Took a spoon and fished it out.

75
00:06:22.882 --> 00:06:24.842
Cut this peach with a knife.

76
00:06:29.472 --> 00:06:32.809
I remember taking it. biting it...

77
00:06:35.853 --> 00:06:37.980
And it was like I'd never had food before.

78
00:06:40.483 --> 00:06:44.529
It was like a lightning bolt
of perfection through simplicity.

79
00:06:46.197 --> 00:06:49.283
Probably the greatest revelation
that I've ever had.

80
00:06:58.793 --> 00:07:01.295
We grew out a couple varieties
of Italian grain.

81
00:07:01.379 --> 00:07:04.674
We grew out some. um. barley
from Magdalena in Mexico.

82
00:07:04.757 --> 00:07:06.926
- Oh. sweet.
- It just loves it out here.

83
00:07:07.009 --> 00:07:10.096
So this is a little petri dish
about what the future's gonna look like.

84
00:07:10.179 --> 00:07:13.182
- Yeah.
- Snippets of all the possibilities.

85
00:07:13.266 --> 00:07:16.394
So these are mostly...
These are all like a flint corn.

86
00:07:16.477 --> 00:07:21.732
We planted this in sort of the same
sort of traditional spacing...

87
00:07:22.817 --> 00:07:25.528
...that you would have seen
in Native American times.

88
00:07:25.611 --> 00:07:28.030
- But isn't this a beautiful plant?
- It's beautiful. man.

89
00:07:28.114 --> 00:07:29.115
You know?

90
00:07:29.198 --> 00:07:30.198
Beautiful.

91
00:07:32.076 --> 00:07:33.870
Let's give some of this grain a run.

92
00:07:33.953 --> 00:07:34.954
Let's do it.

93
00:07:38.708 --> 00:07:41.461
Everything starts
with a tactile approach.

94
00:07:42.253 --> 00:07:43.963
You have to be local

95
00:07:44.797 --> 00:07:47.467
to get close to that.
to get your hands in it.

96
00:07:49.051 --> 00:07:54.515
To get something at source.
or as close to it. is pretty magical.

97
00:07:58.144 --> 00:07:59.937
People not from the desert.

98
00:08:00.021 --> 00:08:02.857
they do not think of it
as being bountiful.

99
00:08:04.442 --> 00:08:06.903
But. in fact.
Chris is in a part of the world

100
00:08:06.986 --> 00:08:10.281
that has deep traditions of wheat growing.

101
00:08:11.032 --> 00:08:13.075
Oh yeah. that feels amazing.

102
00:08:13.159 --> 00:08:16.329
This is warm.
and all that good moisture in there.

103
00:08:17.580 --> 00:08:19.499
Something that Chris discovered

104
00:08:19.582 --> 00:08:23.127
is that Arizona grew wheat
that was going to Italy.

105
00:08:25.213 --> 00:08:30.593
People were using this ideal wheat
for pastas and for pizza making.

106
00:08:30.676 --> 00:08:32.637
and it wasn't staying in Arizona.

107
00:08:33.179 --> 00:08:34.764
That was kind of a happy accident.

108
00:08:36.599 --> 00:08:39.519
Wheat is one of the reasons
he became a great pizza maker.

109
00:08:41.020 --> 00:08:44.899
He has figured out
the exact combination of flour.

110
00:08:45.733 --> 00:08:46.733
of dough work.

111
00:08:47.777 --> 00:08:49.779
and time in the oven

112
00:08:50.821 --> 00:08:53.449
that gets to an idyllic place.

113
00:08:54.534 --> 00:08:57.694
There's a sturdiness to the crust that
goes all the way to the tip of the slice.

114
00:08:58.746 --> 00:09:03.334
and it somehow is able to do that
while still being thin.

115
00:09:05.294 --> 00:09:06.837
And before Chris Bianco.

116
00:09:06.921 --> 00:09:09.465
you kinda thought
it might've been impossible to achieve.

117
00:09:10.550 --> 00:09:14.136
- Watch out for rattlesnakes.
- Yeah. man. Always a buzzkill. You know?

118
00:09:14.220 --> 00:09:15.846
They always ruin the party.

119
00:09:15.930 --> 00:09:18.057
I know. I know.

120
00:09:27.149 --> 00:09:30.194
Chris. this is my favorite picture
of Daddy and I.

121
00:09:30.278 --> 00:09:34.031
- We were just married. It was our first...
- Just married. Ain't that cute?

122
00:09:34.115 --> 00:09:38.202
Look at that. That's Daddy and I.
This was New Year's Day. 1960.

123
00:09:38.869 --> 00:09:41.789
Look at your father.
He looks just like you. Just like you.

124
00:09:41.872 --> 00:09:43.499
- Poor guy. poor guy.
- Yeah.

125
00:09:43.583 --> 00:09:45.501
- That's in New York. Yeah.
- That's a great one.

126
00:09:45.585 --> 00:09:49.255
- There's you as a little boy.
- Before I did anything bad.

127
00:09:49.338 --> 00:09:51.757
- I have a little...
- I remember this pin.

128
00:09:51.841 --> 00:09:54.510
It's about...
about 120 years old.

129
00:09:54.594 --> 00:09:57.597
And my father gave it to me.
I had just been married. He said...

130
00:09:57.680 --> 00:10:00.349
- "In case he's any trouble..." Boom.
- In case he's any trouble...

131
00:10:00.433 --> 00:10:02.727
Anyway... And I cannot tell you

132
00:10:02.810 --> 00:10:07.398
how many pies and breads and tortes
that I've made with this.

133
00:10:07.481 --> 00:10:09.317
That's awesome. What else you got?

134
00:10:09.400 --> 00:10:11.861
Oh. I got other things.
Let me get them real quick.

135
00:10:11.944 --> 00:10:13.487
I was born in the Bronx.

136
00:10:14.196 --> 00:10:15.865
When I was. like. five years old.

137
00:10:16.616 --> 00:10:20.036
I started getting these episodes
where I wasn't able to breathe.

138
00:10:22.079 --> 00:10:24.081
It was the worst thing ever.

139
00:10:24.165 --> 00:10:26.417
I thought. "Maybe I won't make it."

140
00:10:27.168 --> 00:10:29.337
"Maybe I'll just stop breathing one day."

141
00:10:30.463 --> 00:10:31.881
Ended up that I had asthma.

142
00:10:35.176 --> 00:10:36.844
There was no inhalers then.

143
00:10:38.262 --> 00:10:39.639
You had these pills.

144
00:10:40.681 --> 00:10:42.808
If you couldn't breathe.
you'd just chew on one.

145
00:10:44.810 --> 00:10:48.022
If you got bad enough. you'd just go get
a shot of adrenaline at the hospital.

146
00:10:48.105 --> 00:10:50.524
which... not fun. to say the least.

147
00:10:52.860 --> 00:10:54.070
Kept me home.

148
00:10:55.446 --> 00:10:58.115
I loved to play sports.
but I missed a lot of games.

149
00:11:00.785 --> 00:11:03.120
But it allowed me to do something else.

150
00:11:04.288 --> 00:11:06.832
Helped my mom
and my grandmother cook dinner.

151
00:11:09.418 --> 00:11:12.463
My mom was the greatest cook.

152
00:11:13.547 --> 00:11:15.841
Just natural. has a great palate.

153
00:11:17.259 --> 00:11:18.803
She just gets it.

154
00:11:18.886 --> 00:11:21.639
There was lots of love. lots of meatballs.

155
00:11:22.556 --> 00:11:24.684
Chicken cacciatore. which was my favorite.

156
00:11:26.060 --> 00:11:30.314
I got to be around these women
that impacted my life so greatly.

157
00:11:31.440 --> 00:11:32.942
So. from that. you know.

158
00:11:33.025 --> 00:11:35.069
asthma became not something
that was detrimental.

159
00:11:36.445 --> 00:11:38.406
It ended up being an incredible blessing.

160
00:12:00.010 --> 00:12:03.723
My first job in a pizzeria
was a place called Aldo's Pizza

161
00:12:04.432 --> 00:12:06.684
on Croton Avenue in Ossining. New York.

162
00:12:12.189 --> 00:12:16.652
My job was carrying flour
up from the basement

163
00:12:16.736 --> 00:12:18.738
and dump it off to the pizza guy.

164
00:12:20.948 --> 00:12:24.368
And then I graduated
to shredding mozzarella.

165
00:12:26.954 --> 00:12:29.039
You know. I'd get to tug on a few pizzas.

166
00:12:30.708 --> 00:12:32.877
What was amazing about it.

167
00:12:33.711 --> 00:12:38.007
you got to wear an apron.
you got to wear a cool white T-shirt.

168
00:12:38.549 --> 00:12:41.385
You'd get one soda per shift.
which was awesome.

169
00:12:43.012 --> 00:12:44.930
If your friends came in to get a slice.

170
00:12:46.348 --> 00:12:48.184
you felt important

171
00:12:48.267 --> 00:12:50.603
because you had something
that people wanted.

172
00:12:55.232 --> 00:12:58.068
It just really kick-started
to being a part of something.

173
00:12:59.904 --> 00:13:04.158
Pizza made me feel I had a place.
That sense of purpose.

174
00:13:04.992 --> 00:13:06.994
It made me feel like a superhero.

175
00:13:08.412 --> 00:13:09.955
And that was pretty awesome.

176
00:13:23.010 --> 00:13:25.471
So when I was a kid.
I was a very easy child.

177
00:13:25.554 --> 00:13:27.389
Oh yeah. right.

178
00:13:27.473 --> 00:13:30.434
Oh my God. Chris had decided that...

179
00:13:30.518 --> 00:13:33.813
- What did I decide?
- That he didn't love school.

180
00:13:33.896 --> 00:13:36.023
I made you drive me to Little League.

181
00:13:36.106 --> 00:13:39.235
We were sitting in the car. and you said.
"I saw your report card."

182
00:13:39.318 --> 00:13:41.654
"What are you gonna do with yourself?"
And I said.

183
00:13:41.737 --> 00:13:43.322
"I'm gonna be a baseball player."

184
00:13:43.405 --> 00:13:45.908
You said. "Nah. I've seen you.
you're not that good."

185
00:13:46.742 --> 00:13:49.703
- That was a good brush with reality.
- Chris is still...

186
00:13:49.787 --> 00:13:52.122
So many chapters in our lives.

187
00:13:52.206 --> 00:13:55.376
- It was like that. Boom.
- Didn't see that one.

188
00:13:55.459 --> 00:13:58.712
So many years. huh?
I guess we're in for the long haul.

189
00:13:58.796 --> 00:14:01.131
- I think you guys are gonna make it.
- In for the long haul.

190
00:14:01.215 --> 00:14:03.300
You never had
one argument. all these years.

191
00:14:03.384 --> 00:14:07.596
Well. divorce never...
Murder maybe. but not divorce. no.

192
00:14:10.266 --> 00:14:12.977
Asthma was mostly
a nocturnal condition.

193
00:14:13.894 --> 00:14:15.271
I couldn't sleep.

194
00:14:16.480 --> 00:14:19.900
In school. I just felt
if I could stay awake.

195
00:14:19.984 --> 00:14:21.402
I could stay ahead of it.

196
00:14:24.905 --> 00:14:26.699
But I was fucking exhausted.

197
00:14:28.659 --> 00:14:30.077
I didn't do well in high school.

198
00:14:31.537 --> 00:14:33.998
I didn't see college as my place.

199
00:14:36.041 --> 00:14:37.626
I didn't know what to do.

200
00:14:37.710 --> 00:14:41.338
where I fit in.
how I felt... about anything.

201
00:14:43.924 --> 00:14:47.303
My junior year. I dropped out of school.

202
00:14:49.305 --> 00:14:53.267
It's something that
I'm not proud of at all.

203
00:14:55.185 --> 00:14:59.607
My parents challenged me early on
to never fear them.

204
00:15:00.441 --> 00:15:02.109
but fear disappointing them.

205
00:15:04.695 --> 00:15:09.575
I remember the horror going back
to my dad and tellin' him...

206
00:15:12.077 --> 00:15:16.916
Yeah. I can't imagine what my parents
went through. you know.

207
00:15:20.586 --> 00:15:22.922
After Chris
dropped out of high school.

208
00:15:23.005 --> 00:15:25.257
his dad didn't speak to him for a year.

209
00:15:25.341 --> 00:15:28.594
He was upset.
which I think is a normal response.

210
00:15:32.514 --> 00:15:35.684
I decided I don't want to be
someone that let them down.

211
00:15:37.895 --> 00:15:40.105
I knew that I could do two things.

212
00:15:41.815 --> 00:15:42.900
I could be kind...

213
00:15:45.277 --> 00:15:48.197
And I could work as hard
as any other human being that I met.

214
00:15:51.533 --> 00:15:54.620
I could choose to not disappoint anybody.

215
00:16:16.392 --> 00:16:17.267
Oh. hey.

216
00:16:17.351 --> 00:16:20.229
- Oh! You made it after 40 years!
- Just like that.

217
00:16:20.312 --> 00:16:22.147
My mother said. "Go to church."

218
00:16:22.231 --> 00:16:24.692
- Oh. wait a minute!
- So. here I come. here I come.

219
00:16:24.775 --> 00:16:25.609
Not for nothin'.

220
00:16:25.693 --> 00:16:26.902
- Dude...
- How you doing. kid?

221
00:16:26.986 --> 00:16:28.988
You haven't changed.
Just a little gray hair.

222
00:16:29.071 --> 00:16:31.716
You know what's good? The worse eyesight
you get. the better I look.

223
00:16:31.740 --> 00:16:33.742
- My eyes are pretty rough.
- I know. I know.

224
00:16:33.826 --> 00:16:36.328
- There's a lot of memories here.
- Oh yeah.

225
00:16:36.412 --> 00:16:37.955
I remember. I was in college.

226
00:16:38.038 --> 00:16:40.374
your mom came over
and she wanted to put you to work.

227
00:16:40.457 --> 00:16:42.334
My father said.
"You think he can handle it?"

228
00:16:42.418 --> 00:16:43.627
I can't work like you guys!

229
00:16:43.711 --> 00:16:46.422
- Let's go make some mozzarella.
- Let's go. let's go.

230
00:16:46.505 --> 00:16:48.424
Something you can't do in Arizona.

231
00:16:48.507 --> 00:16:50.134
- Yeah?
- Bronx tap water.

232
00:16:50.843 --> 00:16:52.636
I can feel
the Bronx right there. baby.

233
00:16:52.720 --> 00:16:53.887
That's right.

234
00:16:53.971 --> 00:16:58.017
After dropping out of school.
I didn't have a skill set.

235
00:16:58.684 --> 00:17:01.353
I was just looking
for a place to learn something.

236
00:17:01.854 --> 00:17:03.564
Gentile. gentile.

237
00:17:04.106 --> 00:17:07.192
There was a place
that was always like a Mecca to me.

238
00:17:08.027 --> 00:17:09.695
Mike's Deli in the Bronx.

239
00:17:11.113 --> 00:17:12.448
Whenever I went there.

240
00:17:12.948 --> 00:17:16.744
Mike Greco would hand you
slices of prosciutto.

241
00:17:16.827 --> 00:17:17.995
Salute. okay.

242
00:17:18.704 --> 00:17:22.541
While you're waiting to taste it.
he would sing opera.

243
00:17:30.674 --> 00:17:33.385
He would cut mozzarella
in animal shapes.

244
00:17:34.511 --> 00:17:36.388
and all this kinda crazy stuff.

245
00:17:39.558 --> 00:17:40.893
Look at that shine.

246
00:17:41.393 --> 00:17:44.980
Back then. my mozzarella skills
were less than good.

247
00:17:45.064 --> 00:17:47.900
Dave Greco said. "Yeah. man.
Come on by. come on by."

248
00:17:47.983 --> 00:17:49.985
"We'll fix your mozzarella game
up a little bit."

249
00:18:00.162 --> 00:18:03.624
I remember my elbows deep
in boiling hot water.

250
00:18:04.708 --> 00:18:06.460
watching the fat rise.

251
00:18:09.588 --> 00:18:10.964
I was stretching the curds.

252
00:18:12.341 --> 00:18:13.884
and watching them transform.

253
00:18:14.843 --> 00:18:17.012
And I was like.
"How do we know when it's done?"

254
00:18:18.097 --> 00:18:19.306
He was like.

255
00:18:19.389 --> 00:18:20.682
"When it smiles."

256
00:18:21.809 --> 00:18:22.809
And that was it.

257
00:18:33.362 --> 00:18:35.322
I knew what he meant.

258
00:18:36.573 --> 00:18:37.991
There's just presence.

259
00:18:39.118 --> 00:18:40.661
Feels this way.

260
00:18:41.620 --> 00:18:44.456
It's the moment in time
where things come together.

261
00:18:44.540 --> 00:18:47.042
And sometimes there's not a word
for it other than.

262
00:18:47.126 --> 00:18:48.252
"It's when it smiles."

263
00:19:08.021 --> 00:19:10.566
This is a family recipe
that Grandma used to make.

264
00:19:10.649 --> 00:19:12.651
- God bless her.
- That's why we're here today.

265
00:19:12.734 --> 00:19:16.530
'Cause Grandma's recipes
got this store to be what it is today.

266
00:19:16.613 --> 00:19:19.158
That's so beautiful.
I've felt a lot of pasta

267
00:19:19.241 --> 00:19:22.452
through my fingers.
but it's just a beautiful thing. man.

268
00:19:24.288 --> 00:19:27.082
In my early twenties.
I didn't have any money.

269
00:19:28.375 --> 00:19:30.711
and I had no real education.

270
00:19:30.794 --> 00:19:33.338
And I could see no future in New York.

271
00:19:34.298 --> 00:19:35.799
There was nothing for me.

272
00:19:42.681 --> 00:19:44.766
New York's
the smallest little world.

273
00:19:46.602 --> 00:19:48.854
You go to the grocery store.
you go to the deli...

274
00:19:48.937 --> 00:19:49.938
Hey.

275
00:19:50.022 --> 00:19:52.316
...you keep looking at the same faces.

276
00:19:53.775 --> 00:19:56.778
Keep looking out the same window
and not seeing anything new.

277
00:19:59.323 --> 00:20:02.242
I just wanted a place. or a purpose.

278
00:20:05.621 --> 00:20:08.290
I guess I needed
just to go somewhere where...

279
00:20:10.459 --> 00:20:14.046
If I landed.
and you didn't know anything else.

280
00:20:14.129 --> 00:20:15.631
would you choose me?

281
00:20:16.882 --> 00:20:18.258
Would I be welcome?

282
00:20:23.597 --> 00:20:26.308
I love my family.
They're everything to me.

283
00:20:28.143 --> 00:20:29.978
But I decided to leave.

284
00:20:58.840 --> 00:21:00.884
Chris moved
from New York to Phoenix.

285
00:21:00.968 --> 00:21:03.762
not based on. like.
"I've always wanted to move to Phoenix."

286
00:21:03.845 --> 00:21:05.722
or. "I've always wanted
to go to the desert."

287
00:21:06.598 --> 00:21:08.517
It sounded to me much more like a lark.

288
00:21:08.600 --> 00:21:12.020
and that he didn't have a grand plan
for what he was gonna do.

289
00:21:12.938 --> 00:21:14.648
It was kinda this accident.

290
00:21:16.191 --> 00:21:18.360
When I moved to Arizona.

291
00:21:19.111 --> 00:21:21.238
I couldn't articulate what I needed.

292
00:21:21.738 --> 00:21:25.325
I didn't even know what I needed.
It was survival.

293
00:21:29.288 --> 00:21:30.747
I found an apartment.

294
00:21:31.456 --> 00:21:34.376
I didn't know how to do much. but I could
make mozzarella in my apartment.

295
00:21:36.962 --> 00:21:39.089
I was selling that like contraband.

296
00:21:43.593 --> 00:21:46.471
Chris goes door-to-door
with the mozzarella

297
00:21:46.555 --> 00:21:48.807
that he learned to make at Mike's Deli.

298
00:21:49.391 --> 00:21:51.810
trying to sell it to Italian restaurants.

299
00:21:53.020 --> 00:21:55.147
That's totally insane.

300
00:21:56.523 --> 00:21:58.859
But that's just the way Chris was.

301
00:22:03.030 --> 00:22:04.740
I'd show up with mozzarella.

302
00:22:05.490 --> 00:22:06.742
they'd pay cash.

303
00:22:12.622 --> 00:22:14.291
And then I got this opportunity

304
00:22:14.374 --> 00:22:16.835
making pizza in the back
of a grocery store.

305
00:22:18.920 --> 00:22:21.965
The hustle of it kept my mind
and my body busy enough

306
00:22:22.049 --> 00:22:24.134
that I could not think
about anything else.

307
00:22:27.846 --> 00:22:29.681
It helped me get on a good path.

308
00:22:34.227 --> 00:22:38.440
I felt like I could take that hustle
and maybe apply it more.

309
00:22:38.523 --> 00:22:40.233
broaden that horizon a little bit.

310
00:22:55.624 --> 00:22:57.626
So. these are our lemon cucumbers.

311
00:22:59.044 --> 00:23:00.504
You know they're my favorite.

312
00:23:01.463 --> 00:23:04.383
You know what's cool about these
is. like. it's kinda like life itself.

313
00:23:04.466 --> 00:23:06.802
You keep looking from the top.
you don't see much.

314
00:23:06.885 --> 00:23:08.845
- You gotta get down into it.
- Right.

315
00:23:10.555 --> 00:23:11.848
These little babies here.

316
00:23:11.932 --> 00:23:14.601
- Look at that. There it is.
- That's the money right there.

317
00:23:14.684 --> 00:23:15.684
Yeah.

318
00:23:21.108 --> 00:23:23.026
All that needs is. uh.
nothing. really.

319
00:23:23.110 --> 00:23:25.529
Can't beat that.

320
00:23:25.612 --> 00:23:28.532
Again. you guys grow it.
I'll try not to screw it up.

321
00:23:30.700 --> 00:23:33.286
After a few years
at the grocery store.

322
00:23:33.370 --> 00:23:36.581
Chris ended up moving to Santa Fe

323
00:23:36.665 --> 00:23:40.377
and working in a classic
Northern Italian restaurant.

324
00:23:41.086 --> 00:23:43.713
In the old days
of white tablecloth restaurants.

325
00:23:43.797 --> 00:23:46.299
the ingredients came from far away.

326
00:23:47.092 --> 00:23:50.554
It was like. "Oh. let's get
our asparagus from France."

327
00:23:52.055 --> 00:23:55.725
But across the street.
David Tanis had this restaurant.

328
00:23:56.309 --> 00:23:58.270
and they were like. "Why?"

329
00:23:58.353 --> 00:24:02.566
"We're just gonna make food
from the bounty around us."

330
00:24:04.025 --> 00:24:07.529
For Chris it was like.
"Wow. this is so cool."

331
00:24:10.949 --> 00:24:12.242
It was late summer.

332
00:24:12.325 --> 00:24:14.995
In Santa Fe. we were coming up
with a market salad.

333
00:24:15.704 --> 00:24:18.290
It was an amazing farm community there.

334
00:24:18.373 --> 00:24:22.627
But this particular time. there were
some cucumbers but not much else.

335
00:24:23.753 --> 00:24:26.423
One of the cooks. name was Rocky.
he was from Sinaloa. Mexico.

336
00:24:26.506 --> 00:24:29.134
and he had bright red hair
and he was a sweetheart.

337
00:24:30.093 --> 00:24:33.346
I remember Rocky saying to me.
"You're such an idiot."

338
00:24:34.264 --> 00:24:37.142
"Look at all that verdolaga
right by that dumpster."

339
00:24:37.225 --> 00:24:39.478
"All the gringos are just walking by."

340
00:24:42.898 --> 00:24:45.233
I'm like. "Well. dude. man.
what do we do with it?"

341
00:24:46.776 --> 00:24:50.238
Rocky told me to get some
cebollas. pepinos. the cucumber.

342
00:24:54.534 --> 00:24:56.745
I tasted it. It tasted almost like okra.

343
00:24:58.663 --> 00:25:00.373
And it was pretty magical.

344
00:25:02.209 --> 00:25:03.919
It was this revelation.

345
00:25:04.794 --> 00:25:06.838
What are we trampling in our gardens?

346
00:25:09.216 --> 00:25:13.595
Chris learned it's not about
manipulating the ingredients.

347
00:25:13.678 --> 00:25:19.559
It's about finding
the best ingredients around us.

348
00:25:20.143 --> 00:25:24.940
That's where the Chris Bianco
philosophy of pizza was formed.

349
00:25:36.785 --> 00:25:39.663
- There's nothing like that smell.
- No. not at all.

350
00:25:47.003 --> 00:25:49.631
Unleash the hounds. baby.
Unleash the hounds.

351
00:25:55.720 --> 00:25:58.265
- How are you?
- What's happening?

352
00:25:58.348 --> 00:26:00.767
- So. I need a whole one.
- A whole one?

353
00:26:00.850 --> 00:26:02.185
Zion's gonna come by later

354
00:26:02.269 --> 00:26:04.479
if you can get maybe like
two flats of tomatoes.

355
00:26:04.563 --> 00:26:06.940
- I'll put 'em away.
- Is that cool? You're the best.

356
00:26:07.023 --> 00:26:08.942
- Anything for you.
- Oh my God!

357
00:26:10.068 --> 00:26:12.612
- We love you.
- We love you too. I appreciate it.

358
00:26:13.863 --> 00:26:16.575
When Chris comes back to Phoenix.

359
00:26:17.117 --> 00:26:20.579
he sees what a Pizzeria Bianco could be.

360
00:26:21.830 --> 00:26:23.248
And Chris was like.

361
00:26:23.331 --> 00:26:25.875
"We're gonna start
with a blank piece of paper."

362
00:26:26.918 --> 00:26:29.045
"I'm gonna raise the stakes

363
00:26:29.129 --> 00:26:32.173
for the ingredients
that I put on my pizza."

364
00:26:33.675 --> 00:26:38.138
Arizona Department of Agriculture
used to have a statewide farm list

365
00:26:38.221 --> 00:26:39.639
with local ingredients.

366
00:26:40.807 --> 00:26:43.977
Where it'd be like dairy.
fruits. vegetables.

367
00:26:44.060 --> 00:26:46.813
And then. lo and behold.
there was a nut section.

368
00:26:46.896 --> 00:26:49.232
And Lord knows. that was my section.

369
00:26:49.858 --> 00:26:52.319
Um... And I felt at home.

370
00:26:56.281 --> 00:26:59.242
In the southern part of the state.
there's pistachio farms.

371
00:27:00.327 --> 00:27:01.745
And I scored some.

372
00:27:06.041 --> 00:27:08.543
I gave them a little bash
with a mortar and pestle.

373
00:27:11.713 --> 00:27:14.799
Rosemary in Phoenix.
it's growing everywhere.

374
00:27:15.425 --> 00:27:16.676
I got some rosemary.

375
00:27:17.177 --> 00:27:18.345
Awesome onions.

376
00:27:20.639 --> 00:27:21.973
I baked this pizza.

377
00:27:23.683 --> 00:27:26.186
and... alchemy.

378
00:27:29.814 --> 00:27:31.066
The Rosa Pizza.

379
00:27:31.149 --> 00:27:35.195
It's sort of fragrant. singed.

380
00:27:35.862 --> 00:27:39.616
It tastes and smells like the desert.

381
00:27:41.743 --> 00:27:43.745
I had never had a pizza like that.

382
00:27:45.580 --> 00:27:49.042
He took those things
that he learned working with David.

383
00:27:49.125 --> 00:27:51.086
and he applied it to pizza.

384
00:27:54.172 --> 00:27:55.924
Nobody else had ever done that before.

385
00:27:58.635 --> 00:28:01.513
The Rosa was an innovation.

386
00:28:02.681 --> 00:28:04.724
It came out of Chris's mind.

387
00:28:04.808 --> 00:28:06.351
and it came out of Arizona.

388
00:28:18.488 --> 00:28:20.824
- Here you go. Bianco. one more coming up.
- Yeah.

389
00:28:21.950 --> 00:28:22.951
On the way.

390
00:28:30.041 --> 00:28:31.167
Bar. please.

391
00:28:37.549 --> 00:28:40.301
When Chris opened Pizzeria Bianco.

392
00:28:40.385 --> 00:28:43.221
the menu was six pizzas.

393
00:28:44.597 --> 00:28:46.224
Yo.

394
00:28:46.307 --> 00:28:50.395
The ingredients were combined
in ingenious ways.

395
00:28:51.938 --> 00:28:53.481
They were all perfect.

396
00:28:54.899 --> 00:28:57.694
And when people
started to taste his pizza.

397
00:28:58.319 --> 00:29:00.822
to see what he was doing.

398
00:29:01.614 --> 00:29:04.993
Chris Bianco's pizza
attained mythical status.

399
00:29:09.873 --> 00:29:12.375
People started
lining up at 10:00 a.m.

400
00:29:13.501 --> 00:29:16.004
And it didn't open until 5:00 p.m.

401
00:29:16.796 --> 00:29:19.466
They're waiting seven hours!

402
00:29:20.133 --> 00:29:21.885
And it's hot! It's Phoenix!

403
00:29:22.886 --> 00:29:25.346
It was totally insane.

404
00:29:29.434 --> 00:29:31.478
Part of the legend of Chris

405
00:29:32.145 --> 00:29:35.023
was this is the product
of one man's genius.

406
00:29:36.149 --> 00:29:39.736
He basically cooked every pizza.
And that's exciting.

407
00:29:39.819 --> 00:29:42.489
I mean. how can this possibly be?

408
00:29:45.533 --> 00:29:50.705
Every critic in this country
felt they had to make a pilgrimage

409
00:29:50.789 --> 00:29:52.999
to Pizzeria Bianco.

410
00:29:53.082 --> 00:29:55.084
or else your life wasn't complete.

411
00:29:56.127 --> 00:29:59.798
Chris Bianco was the next big thing.

412
00:30:04.469 --> 00:30:09.390
I never found anyone
who called bullshit on his reputation.

413
00:30:10.975 --> 00:30:12.519
That is rare.

414
00:30:14.646 --> 00:30:18.024
He had become. as far as I could tell.

415
00:30:19.442 --> 00:30:21.069
the greatest pizza maker in America.

416
00:30:28.409 --> 00:30:29.953
This is the wheat berry.

417
00:30:30.036 --> 00:30:33.873
then this right here is the endosperm
of the flour and the germ.

418
00:30:33.957 --> 00:30:36.835
And this is the bran.
Looks good. It smells good too.

419
00:30:37.961 --> 00:30:39.801
It'd be nice to do some
test batches with this.

420
00:30:39.838 --> 00:30:42.048
and then we can see
how the flavor profile is.

421
00:30:42.131 --> 00:30:45.677
The opportunity for us is being
a kind of good gateway drug

422
00:30:45.760 --> 00:30:46.886
to better flour.

423
00:30:47.637 --> 00:30:51.349
Even though we try to deny it.
Arizona's an agricultural state.

424
00:30:51.432 --> 00:30:53.432
- You wanna mill some up?
- Yeah. let's mill some up.

425
00:30:56.646 --> 00:31:00.775
Chris had seemingly
reached the top of the pizza mountain.

426
00:31:01.484 --> 00:31:06.739
Everyone wanted
to experience Chris's magic.

427
00:31:08.241 --> 00:31:12.871
And so. he felt enormous
pressure to deliver.

428
00:31:17.584 --> 00:31:20.628
First thing in the morning.
people start to line up.

429
00:31:20.712 --> 00:31:23.006
They would camp out like it was a concert.

430
00:31:25.466 --> 00:31:27.760
I had chefs
that were coming from all over.

431
00:31:28.636 --> 00:31:31.931
Some people are super cool.
Some people are there to check you out.

432
00:31:33.933 --> 00:31:38.187
We had people going through our trash
to see what our secret was.

433
00:31:40.023 --> 00:31:42.066
It was like the stakes had raised.

434
00:31:42.984 --> 00:31:43.984
It's game on.

435
00:31:46.404 --> 00:31:48.031
The more success I had.

436
00:31:48.114 --> 00:31:50.450
the more that I feared
disappointing people.

437
00:31:52.744 --> 00:31:57.332
Anything that was good said about me.
it just made me keep my head down lower.

438
00:31:57.415 --> 00:31:58.750
work harder.

439
00:32:00.043 --> 00:32:01.753
and never leave the kitchen.

440
00:32:04.005 --> 00:32:06.007
I was stood in front
of the oven every day.

441
00:32:08.176 --> 00:32:10.470
I could've been here
23 and a half hours a day.

442
00:32:10.553 --> 00:32:11.553
and someone'd come in.

443
00:32:11.596 --> 00:32:15.808
"I came in the 24th hour. man.
What's going on with you. Mr. Big Shot?"

444
00:32:18.645 --> 00:32:20.688
A thousand people tell me
something positive

445
00:32:20.772 --> 00:32:22.106
and I only hear the one negative.

446
00:32:22.190 --> 00:32:23.691
You know? I only hear that one thing.

447
00:32:26.152 --> 00:32:29.697
I felt if I could only stand in front
of that oven. everything would be okay.

448
00:32:34.160 --> 00:32:39.082
I became more maniacal
about not wanting to let you down.

449
00:32:53.429 --> 00:32:56.557
Come on. girls. All the way down.

450
00:32:57.600 --> 00:33:00.353
All the way down. All the way down.

451
00:33:01.688 --> 00:33:03.731
- We milk 'em twice a day.
- Yeah.

452
00:33:03.815 --> 00:33:05.650
They give about a gallon a day.

453
00:33:06.651 --> 00:33:10.279
But that one gallon can make close to
two pounds of cheese in the winter.

454
00:33:10.363 --> 00:33:12.532
- That yield's amazing. huh?
- It does.

455
00:33:13.032 --> 00:33:14.075
You want a drink?

456
00:33:14.158 --> 00:33:16.494
- Yeah. yeah. Come on. man.
- I think she's got some.

457
00:33:16.577 --> 00:33:18.579
Let's see. Oh yeah.

458
00:33:19.455 --> 00:33:22.166
All right!

459
00:33:22.250 --> 00:33:24.252
Fresh. Fresh drink as you can get.

460
00:33:26.713 --> 00:33:29.841
After working seven days a week
for about six years.

461
00:33:30.508 --> 00:33:33.136
my health.
it started to take a toll on it.

462
00:33:35.013 --> 00:33:38.474
Being around flour my whole life.
inhaling it.

463
00:33:39.225 --> 00:33:41.602
My doctor told me
that I needed to calm down.

464
00:33:42.854 --> 00:33:44.897
They made it like I was dying. which.

465
00:33:45.732 --> 00:33:48.276
you know. maybe there's a part of me
that was in a way.

466
00:33:52.488 --> 00:33:54.365
Chris ends up in the hospital.

467
00:33:55.283 --> 00:33:57.076
He's a lifelong asthmatic.

468
00:33:57.160 --> 00:33:59.162
He has something called Baker's Lung.

469
00:33:59.245 --> 00:34:01.873
due to exposure
of airborne flour and smoke.

470
00:34:02.540 --> 00:34:06.878
Two elements that are absolutely essential
to his life's work.

471
00:34:08.212 --> 00:34:10.256
The doctor tells him.
"If you don't wanna die.

472
00:34:10.339 --> 00:34:12.133
you gotta stop making pizza."

473
00:34:18.181 --> 00:34:19.640
When you tell Chris Bianco.

474
00:34:19.724 --> 00:34:21.726
"Oh yeah. you can't make pizza anymore."

475
00:34:22.769 --> 00:34:26.981
it's like telling Leonardo da Vinci.
"You can't paint anymore."

476
00:34:29.233 --> 00:34:30.485
I was worried about him.

477
00:34:35.031 --> 00:34:36.616
I was really burnt out.

478
00:34:39.660 --> 00:34:40.953
I couldn't sleep.

479
00:34:42.246 --> 00:34:43.498
I couldn't think.

480
00:34:45.750 --> 00:34:49.045
For me to stop making pizza
meant I would disappoint people.

481
00:34:52.215 --> 00:34:54.133
Those days were very difficult.

482
00:34:56.219 --> 00:34:58.054
But I had no place else to go.

483
00:35:03.101 --> 00:35:05.520
When I stood in front of ovens
all those years.

484
00:35:06.312 --> 00:35:07.605
it made me feel...

485
00:35:12.860 --> 00:35:14.700
Like part of that whole thing
of not belonging.

486
00:35:14.737 --> 00:35:16.405
it felt maybe that I belonged.

487
00:35:20.743 --> 00:35:21.953
I'm sorry.

488
